<section xml:id="sec-lines-in-R2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Lines in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m></title>

 <definition xml:id="def-normal-vector">
  <title>(Normal vector)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>\ell</m> be a line in <m>\R^2</m>. A <term>normal vector</term> for <m>\ell</m> is a nonzero 
vector <m>\vect{n}</m> which is orthogonal to <m>\ell</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
A normal vector <m>\vect{n}</m> and one point <m>P</m> on <m>\ell</m> is enough to completely determine the 
line <m>\ell</m>, which we will show by writing the equation for <m>\ell</m> in terms of these two objects. 
Notice that unlike for vectors, the position of <m>\ell</m> in space matters, which is why we need a point 
<m>P</m>.
</p>

<p>Fix <m>P \in \ell</m>, and let <m>X = (x, y)</m> be any point. Let 
<m>\vect{x} = \overrightarrow{OX} = [x, y]</m> and <m>\vect{p} = \overrightarrow{OP}</m>, as shown 
in <xref ref="fig-normal"/>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="fig-normal">
<caption>The normal form of a line</caption>
<image width="60%">
<latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale = 1.2]

\definecolor{greenline}{rgb}{0.1, 0.7, 0.1}

% x-y axis
