<p>
We have
<md>
<mrow>
X \in \ell \amp  \iff \overrightarrow{PX} \text{ is parallel to } \ell       \\
\amp  \iff \overrightarrow{PX} \text{ is orthogonal to } \vect{n} \\
\amp  \iff \overrightarrow{PX} \cdot \vect{n} = 0
</mrow>
</md>
(The symbol <m>\iff</m> stands for `if and only if'.) We also have <m>\overrightarrow{PX} = \overrightarrow{OX} - \overrightarrow{OP}</m>, so
<md>
<mrow>
X \in \ell \amp  \iff (\vect{x} - \vect{p}) \cdot \vect{n} = 0          \\
\amp  \iff \vect{x} \cdot \vect{n} = \vect{p}\cdot \vect{n}
</mrow>
</md>.
This means that <m>\vect{x} \cdot \vect{n} = \vect{p}\cdot \vect{n}</m> is an equation for <m>\ell</m>. 
The next definition summarises this calculation and gives the equation a name.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-normal-form">
<statement>
<p>
The <term>normal form</term> of the equation of a line <m>\ell</m> in <m>\R^2</m> is
<me>
(\vect{x} - \vect{p}) \cdot \vect{n} = 0
</me>
or equivalently
<me>
\vect{x} \cdot \vect{n} = \vect{p}\cdot \vect{n}
</me>
where <m>\vect{n}</m> is a normal vector for <m>\ell</m>, and <m>\vect{p}</m> is the position vector of a point 
on <m>\ell</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
You may be more familiar from high school with equations for lines looking like <m>y = mx +b</m> or 
<m>ax + by = c</m>. We can rearrange the normal form to look like this. Suppose <m>\vect{n} = [a, b]</m> 
and <m>P = (p_1, p_2)</m>, so <m>\vect{p} =[p_1, p_2]</m>. Then 
<m>\vect{n}\cdot \vect{x} = \vect{n}\cdot \vect{p}</m> becomes
  <me>
  [a, b] \cdot [x, y] = [a, b]\cdot [p_1, p_2],
</me>
which is <m>ax + by = ap_1 +bp_2</m>, or <m>ax + by = c</m> where 
<m>c = \vect{n}\cdot \vect{p} = ap_1 + bp_2</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-general-form">
<statement>
<p>
The <term>general form</term> of the equation of a line <m>\ell</m> in <m>\R^2</m> is
<me>
ax +by = c
</me> where <m>\vect{n} = [a, b]</m> is a normal vector for <m>\ell</m> and <m>c = \vect{n}\cdot \vect{p}</m>, 
where <m>\vect{p}</m> is the position vector of a point on <m>\ell</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="ex-normal-form">
<statement>
<p>
The line with general equation <m>3x- y = 9</m> has a normal vector <m>[3, -1]</m>, by looking at its 
coefficients. Any nonzero scalar multiple of <m>[3, -1]</m> would also be a normal vector to the line.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-normal-and-general-form">
<statement>
<p>
Find the normal and general forms of the equation of a line through <m>(2, -1)</m> and perpendicular to 
the vector <m>[3, 4]</m>. We take <m>\vect{n} = [3, 4]</m> and <m>P = (2, -1)</m>, so 
<m>\vect{p} =[2, -1]</m>. We have
<me>
\vect{n}\cdot \vect{p} = [3, 4]\cdot [2, -1] = 6 - 4 = 2,
</me>
so the normal form is <m>[3, 4] \cdot [x, y] = [3, 4] \cdot [2, -1]</m>, which simplifies to
  <me>
  [3, 4]\cdot [x, y] = 2
</me>
and the general form is <m>3x + 4y = 2</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
Notice that if we had picked a different normal vector and a different point on the same line, the normal 
and general forms would look different, although they would still describe the same line.
</p>

