<p>
We will now present a different approach to finding an equation for a line in <m>\R^2</m>. 
It still involves a point and a direction. The difference is that now we will use a vector parallel to the 
line, instead of a vector normal to the line.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-direction-vector">
<statement>
<p>
A <term>direction vector</term> for a line <m>\ell</m> in <m>\R^2</m> is a nonzero vector 
<m>\vect{d} \in\R^2</m> which is parallel to <m>\ell</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
Given a direction vector <m>\vect{d}</m> for a line <m>\ell</m> and a point <m>P\in \ell</m> with 
position vector <m>\vect{p}</m>, we can write down an equation for <m>\ell</m>. Let <m>X</m> be any point 
with position vector <m>\vect{x}</m>. Then
<md>
<mrow>
X \in \ell \amp  \iff \overrightarrow{PX} \text{ is parallel to } \vect{d} \\
\amp  \iff \overrightarrow{PX} = t\vect{d}
</mrow>
</md>,
for some <m>t\in \R</m>. We have <m>\overrightarrow{PX} = \vect{x} - \vect{p}</m>, so
<me>
X \in \ell \iff \vect{x} - \vect{p} = t\vect{d} \iff \vect{x} = \vect{p} + t\vect{d}
</me>.
This is summarised in the next definition.</p>


<definition xml:id="def-vector-form">
<statement>
<p>The <term>vector form</term> of the equation of a line <m>\ell</m> in <m>\R^2</m> which passes 
through a point <m>P</m> with position vector <m>\vect{p}</m>, and is parallel to a vector 
<m>\vect{d}</m>, is
<me>
\vect{x} = \vect{p} + t\vect{d},
</me>
where <m>t \in \R</m> is called a <term>parameter</term>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
The fourth and final form of the equation of a line in <m>\R^2</m> comes from expanding the vector 
form into its components. Suppose <m>\vect{d} = [d_1, d_2]</m>, <m>\vect{p} = [p_1, p_2]</m>, and 
<m>\vect{x} = [x, y]</m>. Then we have
  <me>
  [x, y] = [p_1, p_2] + t[d_1, d_2], \qquad t\in \R
</me>.
Comparing components gives <me>
\left\{
\begin{aligned}
  x \amp  = p_1+ d_1t \\
  y \amp  = p_2 +d_2t \\
\end{aligned}
\right. \qquad t\in\R
</me>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-parametric-eqs">
<statement>
<p>
The <term>parametric equations</term> of a line in <m>\R^2</m> which passes through a point <m>P</m> 
with position vector <m>\vect{p} = [p_1, p_2]</m>, and is parallel to the vector <m>\vect{d} = [d_1, d_2]</m>, 
are
<me>
\left\{
\begin{aligned}
  x \amp  = p_1+ d_1t \\
  y \amp  = p_2 +d_2t \\
\end{aligned}
\right. \qquad t\in\R
</me>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
<term>Summary:</term> A line <m>\ell</m> in <m>\R^2</m> is described by a point and a direction. If we use a 
normal vector to <m>\ell</m>, then the equation is called a normal form when written using vectors, and 
general form when written in components. If we use a direction vector instead, the equation is called a 
vector form when written using vectors, and when written in components we call them parametric equations.
</p>

<p>
To finish this section, we give a few examples and final comments. To find a direction vector 
<m>\vect{d}</m> for a line <m>\ell</m>, find two points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> on <m>\ell</m>. Then 
<m>\vect{d} = \overrightarrow{AB}</m> is a direction vector for <m>\ell</m>. This is illustrated 
in <xref ref="fig-finding_d"/>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="fig-finding_d">
<caption>The vector between two (distinct) points on <m>\ell</m> is a direction vector</caption>
<image width="60%">
<latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
    %points
    \coordinate (A) at (1, 1/3);
    \coordinate (B) at (4.5, 4.5/3);
    
    %lines
    \draw (0, 0) -- (6, 2) node [above right] {$\ell$};
    \draw (A) node [circle, scale=0.55, fill = black] {} node [above] {$A$};
    \draw (B) node [circle, scale=0.55, fill = black] {} node [above] {$B$};
    \draw [vector,->] (A) -- (B) node [midway, below] {$\vect{d} = \overrightarrow{AB}$};
    
\end{tikzpicture}
</latex-image>
</image>
</figure>

<example xml:id="ex-vector-and-para-forms">
<statement>
<p>
Find the vector form and parametric equations for the line <m>\ell</m> through the points 
<m>A= (1, 2)</m> and <m>B = (5, 7)</m>. We can take
<md>
<mrow>
\vect{p} \amp  = \overrightarrow{OA} = [1, 2]                   \\
\vect{d} \amp  = \overrightarrow{AB} = [5, 7] - [1, 2] = [4,5]
</mrow>
</md>.
So a vector form is
  <me>
  [x, y] = [1, 2] + t[4, 5], \qquad t\in \R
</me>
and parametric equations are
<me>
\left\{
\begin{aligned}
  x \amp  = 1 + 4t \\
  y \amp  = 2 +5t  \\
\end{aligned}
\right. \qquad t\in\R.\
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
Like with the normal and general form, the expression of these equations is not unique.
</p>


