<p>
Since a normal vector <m>\vect{n}</m> for a line <m>\ell</m> in <m>\R^2</m> is orthogonal, while a 
direction vector <m>\vect{d}</m> is parallel, this means
<me>
\vect{n}\cdot \vect{d} = 0
</me>.
This observation can help us find <m>\vect{d}</m> if we know <m>\vect{n}</m>, or to find 
<m>\vect{n}</m> if we know <m>\vect{d}</m>. This is shown in the next two examples.
</p>


<example xml:id="ex-dir-vector">
<statement>
<p>
Find a direction vector <m>\vect{d}</m> for the line with normal form <m>x + 2y = 5</m>.
</p>

<p>
A normal vector is <m>\vect{n} = [1, 2]</m>. Let <m>\vect{d} = [d_1, d_2]</m>. We must have
<me>
\vect{n}\cdot \vect{d} = d_1 + 2d_2 = 0,
</me>
so <m>d_1 = -2d_2</m>. Choosing <m>d_2 = 1</m>, a direction vector is <m>\vect{d} = [-2, 1]</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-finding-normal-vector">
<statement>
<p>
Find a normal vector for the line with parametric equations
<me>
\left\{
\begin{aligned}
  x \amp  = -1 + 2t \\
  y \amp  = 4 +3t   \\
\end{aligned}
\right. \qquad t\in\R
</me>.
A direction vector is <m>\vect{d} = [2, 3]</m>, so <m>\vect{n} = [-3, 2]</m> is a normal vector, 
since <m>\vect{d}\cdot \vect{n} = 2(-3) + 2\cdot 3 = 0.</m>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

</section>